Looking at the Guava implementation in `ListenableFutureCoroutine`, I can see the key insight in the comments (lines 287-296):

```kotlin
/**
 * ...
 * Any error that occurs after successfully cancelling a [ListenableFuture] is lost.
 * The contract of [Future] does not permit it to return an error after it is successfully cancelled.
 * On the other hand, we can't report an unhandled exception to [CoroutineExceptionHandler],
 * otherwise [Future.cancel] can lead to an app crash which arguably is a contract violation.
 * ...
 */
```

And importantly, the `onCancelled` method in `ListenableFutureCoroutine` does NOT call `handleCoroutineException`:

```kotlin
override fun onCancelled(cause: Throwable, handled: Boolean) {
    // Note: if future was cancelled in a race with a cancellation of this
    // coroutine, and the future was successfully cancelled first, the cause of coroutine
    // cancellation is dropped in this promise. A Future can only be completed once.
    //
    // This is consistent with FutureTask behaviour. A race between a Future.cancel() and
    // a FutureTask.setException() for the same Future will similarly drop the
    // cause of a failure-after-cancellation.
    future.completeExceptionallyOrCancel(cause)
}
```

This is the key fix! The `CompletableFutureCoroutine` in `kotlinx-coroutines-jdk8` should similarly NOT call `handleCoroutineException`. It should just always try to complete the future and not bother with the global exception handler.

Looking at the current code:
```kotlin
override fun onCancelled(cause: Throwable, handled: Boolean) {
    if (!future.completeExceptionally(cause) && !handled) {
        handleCoroutineException(context, cause)
    }
}
```

When a Future is cancelled first and the coroutine subsequently throws an exception, `future.completeExceptionally(cause)` returns `false` due to the future being already completed/cancelled. The `!handled` condition remains true since the exception wasn't handled by any parent. This leads to calling `handleCoroutineException(context, cause)`, which ultimately crashes the application.

I see the solution is to eliminate the `handleCoroutineException` call entirely, mirroring the approach in the Guava implementation. This prevents potential app crashes and respects the Future contract by silently dropping exceptions after cancellation.

